programme.title: Breakfast
programme.desc: Charlie Stayt and Naga Munchetty present national and international news, plus sports reports, weather forecasts and arts and entertainment features. Including NewsWatch at 7.45.

programme.title: Saturday Kitchen Live
programme.desc: Michel Roux Jr is joined by chefs Anna Jones and James Tanner, and special guest Brenda Blethyn, while Olly Smith selects the wines to go with the studio dishes.

programme.title: Tom Kerridge's Fresh Start
programme.desc: Tom demonstrates ways that the whole family can help out cooking in the kitchen, and shares family favourite recipe ideas that are healthy and easy to prepare. First, Tom and his son Acey make filo pastry triangles with feta cheese, before he drops by to teach ten-year-old Nihirika and seven year-old Krish how to cook simple Asian-style glazed chicken thighs in their family home.

programme.title: Football Focus
programme.desc: Dan Walker and guests review the week's headlines and look ahead to forthcoming fixtures, including Arsenal v Chelsea and Liverpool v Crystal Palace in the Premier League.

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the opening semi-final, played over the best of 11 frames on day seven at Alexandra Palace in London. At the corresponding stage of last year's tournament, eventual winner Mark Allen overcame John Higgins 6-3 to book his place in the showpiece match, where he would face Englishman Kyren Wilson. Coverage continues on BBC2.

programme.title: Final Score
programme.desc: Jason Mohammad presents a round-up of the classified results and this afternoon's news from the Premier League, EFL and Scotland.

programme.title: The Time It Takes
programme.desc: Joe Lycett and Alison Hammond host the game show, in which contestants face challenges including covering a person in wrapping paper and mopping up gravy using a flannel.

programme.title: Pointless Celebrities
programme.desc: Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman present a writers special edition of the general knowledge quiz. Contestants are Richard Madeley, Dreda Say Mitchell, John O'Farrell, Lise Mayer, Jenny Colgan, Jane Fallon, Richard Stilgoe and Don Black.

programme.title: Michael McIntyre's Big Show
programme.desc: The host looks back over his favourite surprises and pranks from the last four series of his Big Show. Ed Balls, Alexander Armstrong and Carol Vorderman talk about what it was like to hand over their phone in Celebrity Send to All, while Gino D'Acampo relives what it was like waking up and finding Michael in his bedroom on Midnight Gameshow. Closing the show will be unexpected star Anush Hydros, who is now starring on the West End stage.

programme.title: The Greatest Dancer
programme.desc: Alesha Dixon and Jordan Banjo host the dancing contest, featuring performers from a variety of styles, including ballet, jazz, street, ballroom, contemporary and disco, competing for a £50,000 prize and the chance to showcase their skills on the next series of Strictly Come Dancing. Cheryl, Matthew Morrison and Oti Mabuse are on hand to help the competitors make the best use of their talents - but which contestants get to go through the show's magic mirror and make it through to the next round is entirely in the hands of the studio audience.

programme.title: Casualty
programme.desc: Alicia finds out that she has been offered a place on a coveted paediatric fellowship in Manchester, forcing her to make a decision on her future. Elsewhere, Marty's lies begin to catch up with him, while Elle is disappointed when she has to hand back to reins as clinical lead to a returning Connie.

programme.title: Match of the Day
programme.desc: Gary Lineker presents highlights of the latest Premier League matches, including Arsenal v Chelsea at the Emirates Stadium and Liverpool v Crystal Palace at Anfield. Both league fixtures between the Gunners and the Blues last season ended in draws, including a 2-2 result on this ground. However, Maurizio Sarri's side overcame Unai Emery's men 3-2 in this season's reverse fixture at Stamford Bridge, thanks to goals from Pedro, Alvaro Morata and Marcos Alonso. Plus, action from Bournemouth v West Ham United at the Vitality Stadium, Manchester United v Brighton & Hove Albion at Old Trafford, Newcastle United v Cardiff City at St James' Park, Southampton v Everton at St Mary's Stadium, Watford v Burnley at Vicarage Road and Wolverhampton Wanderers v Leicester City at Molineux.

programme.title: The NFL Show
programme.desc: Mark Chapman looks ahead to the Conference Championship games, joined by former NFL stars Osi Umenyiora and Jason Bell.

programme.title: Ill Manors
programme.desc: A drug dealer returns to his London council estate after 15 years in prison, which sets in motion a chain of violent events that impacts on the lives of various residents struggling to survive in the community, including a small-time crook torn between his morals and his loyalty to his ruthless friend. Crime drama, starring Riz Ahmed, Nick Sagar and Keith Coggins.(n)

programme.desc: The latest political news and debate from a regional perspective.(n)

programme.title: Songs of Praise

programme.title: Lifeline
programme.desc: Nick Knowles presents an appeal on behalf of Walking with the Wounded, a charity which helps vulnerable veterans integrate back into society and sustain their independence.(n)

programme.title: Porridge
programme.desc: Prison-based comedy from writers Dick Clement and Ian La Frenais, who penned the initial series aired in the 1970s. Cyber criminal Fletch has taken to helping his fellow inmates with appeals and letters home to loved ones, but finds things become complicated when cellmate Barry's girlfriend pays a visit. Kevin Bishop stars as Nigel ?Fletch' Fletcher, grandson of original offender Norman Stanley.(n)

programme.title: Bargain Hunt
programme.desc: The antiques show comes from Wetherby racecourse, West Yorkshire, where experts David Harper and Philip Serrell offer advice to two teams trying to find items they can sell at auction. Presenter Tim Wonnacott also visits Harewood House.(n)

programme.title: Money for Nothing
programme.desc: Sarah Moore is in Altrincham hoping to find some hidden gems she can transform and send off to a new home. Meanwhile, Bex Simon almost meets her match with a filing cabinet.(n)

programme.title: Escape to the Country
programme.desc: Jules Hudson is on a house-hunting mission in the Somerset countryside with a keen gardening couple who have £700,000 pounds, and hopes of enjoying the county's mild climate.(n)

programme.title: Pointless Celebrities
programme.desc: Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman invite another selection of celebrities from the world of radio broadcasting to take part in the unorthodox quiz show. As ever, success can only be achieved by guessing the least likely correct answers to questions posed to members of the public. This time, Mark Steel teams up with Marcus Brigstocke, Nicky Campbell partners Rachel Burden, Liz Kershaw allies with DJ Nihal, and Shaun Keaveny joins forces with Nemone.(n)

programme.title: Countryfile
programme.desc: Anita Rani tastes a local cheese with a long heritage in Wiltshire, where Matt Baker discovers the incredible work of a care farm that is changing children's lives. Paralympian Hannah Cockroft is in the Highlands of Scotland meeting a young gamekeeper to find out what the job entails and Tom Heap investigates how far people are prepared to go to keep the UK's farms free from disease. Including Weather for the Week Ahead.(n)

programme.title: Antiques Roadshow
programme.desc: Fiona Bruce presents the show from Crathes Castle, Aberdeenshire, where finds brought in to be valued include a collection of signed Harry Potter books, ornate silver from Iona, a German art deco figurine, an intricate Italian bracelet, and a baseball cap with an unusual story to tell.(n)

programme.title: Call the Midwife
programme.desc: Lucille treats an elderly hoarder (Annette Crosbie) suffering from a malodorous leg ulcer, and fears that living surrounded by towering piles of rubbish, books and tins of food will have a serious effect on her recovery. Sister Hilda has a challenging case on her hands when a family newly arrived from Ghana are found to be suffering from an unidentified illness, and Violet runs for a place on the local council, but Fred is not convinced she can make a difference to the community, placing more faith in the Civil Defence Corps.(n)

programme.title: Les Miserables
programme.desc: Cosette has grown into a teenager, and to Valjean's dismay, questions her closeted life and is desperate for a new start in Paris. The opportunity presents itself when she meets Pontmercy's son Marius, who has turned his back on his family after learning the truth about his father, and now lives in a squalid tenement, where he catches the eye of the daughter of a criminal family. Javert ascends through the ranks of the police, and believes he is closing in on his goal.(n)

programme.title: Match of the Day 2
programme.desc: Mark Chapman reviews the day's Premier League action, introducing highlights of Huddersfield Town v Manchester City and Fulham v Tottenham Hotspur. The relegation-threatened Terriers conceded six goals against the champions early in the season, and had only won one of their last 11 home games in this fixture. At Craven Cottage, Claudio Ranieri's men faced a Spurs side that had triumphed on their last four visits. There's also a round-up of all the goals from Saturday's eight games, including Arsenal v Chelsea.(n)

programme.title: Jonathan Pie's American Pie
programme.desc: Spoof documentary in which a bumbling British reporter is sent across the Atlantic to get the inside scoop on the US midterm elections.(n)

programme.title: The One Show

programme.title: Inside Out
programme.desc: Documentary series focusing on regional stories of interest.(n)

programme.title: EastEnders
programme.desc: Kat revels in looking after her kids, while Stacey worries about Hayley. Mick is still feeling down and refuses to speak to Johnny over the phone, only for his day to go from bad to worse when football mum Megan to arrive, complaining that the team has folded. As the two find themselves at loggerheads, the landlord quickly realises he is fighting a losing battle.(n)

programme.title: Panorama
programme.desc: An official inquiry has found that more than 450 patients had their lives shortened at Gosport War Memorial Hospital in 1990s, with many being given fatal doses of painkillers even though they were not terminally ill and had only been admitted for rehabilitation following routine operations. Reporter Richard Bilton investigates the evidence and challenges those who may be to blame for the deaths.(n)

programme.title: Silent Witness
programme.sub-title: To Brighton, to Brighton - Part One
programme.desc: Part one of two. During a heatwave in Brighton, the Lyell team is summoned to a waste dump where a body part has been found. The search is on to recover the other dismembered remains and piece together the victim's body, which is covered in intricate Japanese tattoos. Away from the lab, Nikki has some news that she desperately wants to share with Matt, but must wait until he visits from America. Forensic crime drama, starring Emilia Fox, David Caves, Richard Lintern and Liz Carr, with Samantha Bond.(n)

programme.title: Imagine
programme.desc: Alan Yentob follows the British playwright, whose award-winning work takes audiences to the very heart of the defining political events that shape all our lives. The film delves into Graham's acclaimed hits including This House, Labour of Love and Ink, alongside his recent Channel 4 drama Brexit: The Uncivil War, while also exploring his own personal story and what drives him to create such unique political theatre.(n)

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the conclusion of the final from Alexandra Palace, London, where the first player to reach 10 frames will win the Paul Hunter Trophy. Both players were battling it out for their maiden Triple Crown title in last year's showpiece match, and it was Northern Ireland's Mark Allen who prevailed 10-7 against Kyren Wilson of England. Little could separate the two players until Allen moved 6-5 ahead before notching a break of 119 in the next. Wilson rallied to pull it back to 8-7, but his opponent was able to respond to become the first man from his country to win the title since Dennis Taylor in 1987 and collected a £200,000 prize for his efforts.(n)

programme.sub-title: Tennis: Australian Open Highlights: 2019 Day Eight

programme.title: Celebrity Antiques Road Trip

programme.desc: Sanjeev Bhaskar assesses the legacies and achievements of Mohandas Gandhi, Helen Keller, Martin Luther King Jr and Emmeline Pankhurst - four of the 20th century's greatest activists. Gandhi employed non-violent tactics to help secure independence for India, while the deaf and blind Keller used her fame to fight for the rights of marginalised people everywhere. King was arguably the most influential figure of the black civil rights movement in the US, while Pankhurst was a controversial figure in the fight for women's suffrage.(n)

programme.desc: The latest research into one of the most mysterious and common human experiences - pain. programme.title: The Secret Life of the Sun
programme.desc: Using satellite images and the expertise of Britain's leading solar scientists, Kate Humble and Helen Czerski investigate the inner workings of the star and the influence its cycles of activity have on Earth. programme.title: Wonders of the Universe
